i>birel</i>) ‘reddish brown’, referring perhaps to complexion or hair color. This was occasionally used by Normans as a personal name, perhaps a nickname substituted for the personal name. The word also denoted a coarse woollen cloth of this color, so the surname may sometimes refer to dress, or it may be a nickname for a maker of the cloth, a <i>bureller</i>.","habitational name from Burwell in Lincolnshire, see   Burwell  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Burrel was born in 1508, in Cottingham, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Marion. He died after 1535, in Badby, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1508–after 1535":"1508–pärast 1535","1508–1530":"1508–1530","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1508–1535":"1508–1535","1535":"1535","after 1535":"pärast 1535","Abt 1530":"umbes 1530","Aft 1530":"pärast 1530","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1508":"1508","of Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England","Cottingham, Yorkshire, England":"Cottingham, Yorkshire, England","Badby Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1508–after 1535":"1508–1535 jälkeen","1508–1530":"1508–1530","1530–1563":"1530–1563","1508–1535":"1508–1535","1535":"1535","after 1535":"1535 jälkeen","Abt 1530":"noin 1530","Aft 1530":"1530 jälkeen","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1508":"1508","of Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire